[10] USA (Texas)
Date: Fri 16 Aug 2013
Source: Star-Telegram [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.star-telegram.com/2013/08/16/5086611/measles-found-in-tarrant-county.html


Nine of the 14 cases of measles reported in Texas this year [2013] are in Tarrant County, and 4 of the others are elsewhere in North Texas, public health officials report. Seven of the Tarrant County cases were confirmed Friday [15 Aug 2013], said Vanassa Joseph, a spokeswoman for Tarrant County Public Health.

The 9 Tarrant County cases have been traced to a parent who traveled to a foreign country and brought back the infection, Joseph said. A child of that parent came down with measles. The 7 cases confirmed Friday [15 Aug 2013] were people who came in contact with the parent or child, she said. "The number of people involved is changing very rapidly and is not static," said Dr. Russell Jones, chief epidemiologist for Tarrant County Public Health. "Whatever I say now will change very quickly."

All 9 people live in northern Tarrant County and have been asked to "self-isolate," Joseph said. No measles cases were reported in the state or Tarrant County last year [2012]. In 2011, the state had 6 cases, and the county had 2. Before that, measles had not been reported in Tarrant County for 17 years.

Two cases each have been reported this year [2013] in Dallas and Denton counties, with one case in Harris County, said Christine Mann, spokeswoman for the Texas Department of State Health Services. All the state cases are "import-associated," meaning that someone contracted the disease abroad, Mann said.

Although often recognized by the rash that spreads over the body, measles is a respiratory disease caused by a virus. It lives in the mucus of the nose and throat and is spread by coughing and sneezing. "Measles is the most deadly of all childhood rash/fever illnesses," according to the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention website. Six to 20 percent of people who contract the disease will get an ear infection, diarrhea or pneumonia. One in 1000 people with measles develops brain inflammation, or encephalitis. Of every 1000 children who get measles, one or 2 will die, the CDC says. Pneumonia is the complication that most often causes death in young children. Ear infections can lead to permanent hearing loss. Pregnant women who get measles may have a miscarriage, give birth prematurely, or have a low-birth-weight baby.

The parent and child in northern Tarrant County who were initially infected have recovered but spread the virus for about 9 days, according to health officials. Investigators are tracking down people who have been in close contact with the pair or with the other 7 people infected.

Three healthcare providers have reported individuals who might have the disease, Jones said.

