[11] USA (Texas)
Date: Fri 16 Aug 2013
Source: My Fox Houston [edited]
http://www.myfoxhouston.com/story/23159185/texas-issues-mesales-alert


The Texas Department of State Health has issued a measles alert for the state.

One confirmed case is here in the Houston area. The state says they have had 4 new confirmed cases this month [August 2013], bringing the total to 9 for the year [2013]. The 4 most recent confirmed cases are all from Tarrant County, but the other cases this year have been in Dallas County (2), 2 in Denton County and one in Harris County.

Measles is so contagious that if a person infected with the disease coughs or sneezes, 90 percent of the people close to that person who are not immune or vaccinated will become infected with the measles virus. The incubation period of measles is about 2 weeks from exposure to onset of rash on the face, and then spreads to the body. People are contagious about 4 days before the onset of rash to 4 days after the appearance of rash. Other symptoms include fever higher than 101 F, cough, runny nose and sore eyes.

The State Health Department is asking doctors to consider measles in their diagnosis if any patient has a rash and a fever. Immunizations are the best protection against the spread of measles.

[Byline: Kathryn Yglecias]

